The paper proposes a method for learning driver models using a synthetic dataset, which involves encoding vehicle trajectories and distinguishing between different driver behaviors. This involves simultaneous policy learning and latent state inference, which suggests that the paper could belong to the categories of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the use of vehicle trajectories and driver behavior could also suggest computer vision (cs.CV) and robotics (cs.RO) as potential categories. Finally, the paper involves learning policies for driving, which could also suggest systems and control (cs.SY) as a possible category.
